00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:04.774
absolutely possible with and
through and in technology.

00:06:04.774 --> 00:06:06.190
And I think that
what you're about

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:09.790
is figuring out
how to amplify that

00:06:09.790 --> 00:06:14.780
and to explore all the
possibilities in that.

00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:20.380
So I think of listening
as a basic social art.

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:22.930
I think of social
art and virtues

00:06:22.930 --> 00:06:26.860
as spiritual technologies.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.470
And that is to say,
just a tool for the art

00:06:29.470 --> 00:06:33.760
and craft of living,
and for a deepened,

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:37.540
more generative-- which
is a nuanced unproductive,

00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:40.570
although it can be productive--
but a more deepened,

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:44.650
generative, higher-quality,
human experience.

00:06:44.650 --> 00:06:47.630
And the interesting thing--

00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:48.970
so it is a basic social art.

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:50.740
I think it's something
we know how to do

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:53.530
or we've known how to do,
but we've actually unlearned.

00:06:56.230 --> 00:07:00.530
I think that, growing
up in this culture,

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:06.380
we learn that listening is--
or the experience we have,

00:07:06.380 --> 00:07:08.930
which we internalize to be
about what listening is about--

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:12.710
is to be quiet while the
other person says what

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:15.350
they have to say
until it's time for me

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:17.690
to say what I have to say.

00:07:17.690 --> 00:07:22.400
But actually, listening
is not about being quiet.

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:25.370
The being quiet
is a side-effect.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:29.600
Listening is about
being present.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:32.150
And as I just said,
interestingly, you

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:36.330
can be present online as well.

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:40.190
And so because we've
unlearned this thing,

00:07:40.190 --> 00:07:41.890
I think it's interesting
to think about,

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:46.160
what are it's really
basic component parts?

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:52.510
For me, listening brings a
quality, musters a quality,

00:07:52.510 --> 00:07:54.365
of generosity.

00:07:54.365 --> 00:07:57.940
And a spiritual
technology is always

00:07:57.940 --> 00:07:59.140
working in two directions.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:03.100
It's inner work as much
as it's outer work.

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:05.740
So especially in this
world we inhabit now,

00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:09.730
and with so many things
we're fighting about

00:08:09.730 --> 00:08:13.540
and so many things
were fearful about,

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:16.160
this is not as easy
as it sounds, right?

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:19.330
In fact, it's not
very instinctive.

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:24.670
To me, a generous listener,
a definition of that would be

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:30.010
wanting to understand the
humanity behind the words

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:32.620
of the other-- so it's not just
about the words that are going

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:34.120
to pass between us--

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:39.370
and wanting to bring your own
best words and your best ideas

00:08:39.370 --> 00:08:42.010
into the conversation.

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:45.220
You have to muster
also, in yourself,

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:49.720
a real curiosity to bring that
kind of generosity to bear.

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:53.410
And again, this is
really a withered muscle.

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:58.490
The thing about curiosity is
you can't actually fake it.

00:08:58.490 --> 00:09:03.760
And again, whether
we're online or offline,

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:08.140
we, at an animal level, when we
encounter another human being,

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:11.710
absolutely know whether
they're really curious

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:14.710
or whether they're just
asking us a question.

00:09:14.710 --> 00:09:18.290
We know that in our bodies.

00:09:18.290 --> 00:09:23.680
So really, even just
this basic component

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:26.680
of the art of living,
of being curious,

00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:29.260
becomes a spiritual discipline.

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:30.730
Or if you don't
like that language,

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:33.520
it becomes a muscle that
we need to flex and flex

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:38.470
so that it, again, starts
to feel like instinct,

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:39.730
starts to feel natural.

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:46.420
Listening involves
vulnerability.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:52.900
One litmus test about whether
you have actually gotten

00:09:52.900 --> 00:09:54.850
yourself to a curious
place that you

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:56.860
can ask-- whether
you go into a room,

00:09:56.860 --> 00:09:59.530
whether that's a virtual
room or a physical room--

00:09:59.530 --> 00:10:03.970
is are you willing
to be surprised?

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:07.450
And again, we walk
into all of our spaces

00:10:07.450 --> 00:10:12.010
these days so guarded,
so clear about what

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:14.650
we have to say, what
we have to present,

00:10:14.650 --> 00:10:17.620
what we have to
protect, and also

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:22.240
so clear about what we think
those other people stand for.

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:29.260
So to be willing to be surprised
is an unnatural move right now.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:31.510
And then the final piece
of this that I want to add

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:36.550
is that, actually,
in many of the spaces

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:38.920
we are currently working with
and living in and meeting

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.990
each other in, it
wouldn't actually

00:10:40.990 --> 00:10:44.620
be reasonable to ask
other people to surprise

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:48.140
themselves or surprise us.

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:49.790
So there's a piece of this--

00:10:49.790 --> 00:10:54.490
I think that the
social art of listening

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:58.420
is intimately connected with
the virtue of hospitality,

00:10:58.420 --> 00:10:59.900
another spiritual technology.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.320
One thing I love
about hospitality--

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.500
it's a gateway to all
the other great virtues--

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:07.135
compassion or love.

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:12.846
It's much easier.

00:11:12.846 --> 00:11:13.970
It's an easier entry point.

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:16.510
You don't actually
have to love someone

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:18.526
to be hospitable towards them.

00:11:18.526 --> 00:11:19.900
You don't have to
agree with them

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:21.150
to be hospitable towards them.

00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:26.140
You don't even have to like them
to be hospitable towards them.

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:30.990
But we know, in
our analog lives--

00:11:30.990 --> 00:11:34.920
and I think, maybe, we're
learning in our online lives--

00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:42.060
that the space you create
absolutely limits or expands

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:44.370
what is possible that
will happen there.

00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:47.970
There is a difference
between creating a space

00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:54.710
with a welcome and an ethos
or just opening the door so

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:56.060
that anything can happen.

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:02.300
Something that's
very clear to me

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:05.630
that I think a lot about, that
it's fun to say in this room,

00:12:05.630 --> 00:12:14.630
is that, to me, the digital
world is just a new canvas

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:18.020
for the old human condition.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:19.820
There's nothing
that happens online

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:23.000
that doesn't have an offline,
although, things can absolutely

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.500
get amplified.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:30.420
It's the good, the
bad, and the ugly.

00:12:30.420 --> 00:12:33.810
We're encountering the trolls.

00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:38.580
We all walk around with
trollish places in our psyches.

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:44.221
Now they have this public
room to run around in, right?

00:12:44.221 --> 00:12:44.763
But they're--

00:12:44.763 --> 00:12:46.637
DANIELLE KRETTEK: That's
such a great visual.

00:12:46.637 --> 00:12:47.160
Just like--

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:48.076
KRISTA TIPPETT: Right?

00:12:48.076 --> 00:12:48.971
But think about it!

00:12:48.971 --> 00:12:49.470
Yeah.

00:12:53.470 --> 00:12:58.950
So this has always been
true that the quality

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:01.740
of the encounter, of the
listening, of the relationship,

00:13:01.740 --> 00:13:04.800
of the possibility of what can
happen between two people--

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:07.540
whether they agree with each
other or don't or similar

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:08.240
or don't--

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:12.165
is very much affected
by creating this space.

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:18.930
And I think there's
just a real need, again,

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:22.350
in the physical world as
much as in the online world,

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:24.260
to create alternative spaces--

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.100
and I'll say it
again-- where it would

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:30.600
be reasonable to ask any of us
to walk in and bring our best

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:36.360
selves and be looking
for the good in the other

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:40.200
and be willing to surprise
ourselves and be truly inviting

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:43.050
other people to surprise us.

00:13:43.050 --> 00:13:47.910
So I guess the other thing
I would want to just mention

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:50.910
that I absolutely
think of, in terms

00:13:50.910 --> 00:13:57.120
of a companion to
listening, is the art

00:13:57.120 --> 00:14:00.570
of asking better questions.

00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:06.450
In American life, we
mostly trade in answers.

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:11.280
And we actually mostly
trade in competing answers.

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:15.870
And a lot of what
calls itself a question

00:14:15.870 --> 00:14:21.940
or presents as a question
is actually not questioning.

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:27.990
It's tools or weapons to
incite or corner or catch

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:30.000
or, at least, entertain.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.060
And this is certainly true
in my field of journalism.

00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:35.340
The question is
often about how it

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:37.740
makes the journalist
look and not really

00:14:37.740 --> 00:14:43.560
about what it's going to elicit.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:46.200
What I want to point out in
that spectacle, which we're all

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:49.350
very familiar with,
is how powerful

00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:53.700
a form of words a question is.

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:56.210
The way I've come
to experience it

00:14:56.210 --> 00:15:01.950
is that questions elicit
answers in their likeness.

00:15:01.950 --> 00:15:06.840
Answers rise or fall to
the questions they meet.

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:11.130
And in the negative
expression of that,

00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:17.370
which we're very
familiar with from media,

00:15:17.370 --> 00:15:21.480
it's almost impossible to
meet a simplistic question

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:25.410
with anything but a
simplistic answer.

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:31.570
It's almost impossible to
transcend a combative question.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:37.570
But the positive side of that
is that it's almost impossible

00:15:37.570 --> 00:15:41.830
to resist a generous question.

00:15:41.830 --> 00:15:43.210
And we've all had
that experience

00:15:43.210 --> 00:15:47.530
that there is something
life-giving about asking

00:15:47.530 --> 00:15:49.305
a better question.

00:15:49.305 --> 00:15:50.680
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
Can I ask you--

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:51.120
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah?

00:15:51.120 --> 00:15:52.690
DANIELLE KRETTEK: May
I ask you a question?

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:53.260
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yes, you may.

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:53.970
Yeah.

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:55.857
AUDIENCE: Good practice.

00:15:55.857 --> 00:15:57.190
DANIELLE KRETTEK: I know, right?

00:15:57.190 --> 00:15:58.600
You're like, if it's a good one.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:15:59.590
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:00.570
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
Is it generous?

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:01.444
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:16:01.444 --> 00:16:05.230
DANIELLE KRETTEK: So what I'm
hearing, as you're speaking,

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:08.980
is there is this sense of
an opening that happens when

00:16:08.980 --> 00:16:10.660
there is a generous presence.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:12.460
There is an opening
in the question.

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:14.360
There's an opening in
the space between you

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:15.970
where things can be put there.

00:16:15.970 --> 00:16:17.890
I'm so curious.

00:16:17.890 --> 00:16:20.020
You mentioned it the other
night with the word--

00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:22.570
you set an intention before
you go in-- the listening

00:16:22.570 --> 00:16:23.620
before the listening.

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:27.050
And I'm just curious, how
does that work for you?

00:16:27.050 --> 00:16:28.450
How do you cultivate
that opening

00:16:28.450 --> 00:16:29.950
in yourself, that invitation?

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:34.080
Because it is that first step
of hospitality is open the door,

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:36.520
and come into this space
that we can be in together.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:37.060
I'm just so curious.

00:16:37.060 --> 00:16:37.960
KRISTA TIPPETT:
So when I'm having

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:39.370
a conversation or an interview?

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:40.780
DANIELLE KRETTEK: When
you're having a conversation

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:42.821
and when you're figuring
out the right questions,

00:16:42.821 --> 00:16:44.800
the questions that have
the opening in them.

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:45.675
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:51.310
Well, I do actually think
in terms of hospitality

00:16:51.310 --> 00:16:53.150
in the work I do.

00:16:53.150 --> 00:16:55.330
And so I think of
the preparation

00:16:55.330 --> 00:17:01.300
I do for an interview
as work of hospitality.

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:06.730
Because again, so
much is determined

00:17:06.730 --> 00:17:11.680
about how an encounter is going
to go in the initial moments

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:13.660
before words are spoken.

00:17:13.660 --> 00:17:18.890
So just setting
that table, which

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:21.787
is an image of a certain
kind of hospitality,

00:17:21.787 --> 00:17:22.745
but it's the same idea.

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:32.610
When we don't do that, then
the most obvious things

00:17:32.610 --> 00:17:36.660
about us that we're all carrying
out front right now just

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:40.060
define what's possible.

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:42.900
And so what I'm interested
in is how can we--

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:45.700
not solve all the problems
or make it that we're--

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:47.700
because I really want to
be in rooms with people

00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:49.390
I disagree with and
who are different

00:17:49.390 --> 00:17:52.050
and who I need to
learn from and who

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:54.270
I know I want to share
life with, even if I really

00:17:54.270 --> 00:17:56.190
don't understand them--

00:17:56.190 --> 00:17:57.090
not violent people.

00:17:57.090 --> 00:17:58.381
But most people aren't violent.

00:17:58.381 --> 00:18:00.270
There's this huge swath
in the middle where

00:18:00.270 --> 00:18:03.910
those fellow humans are there.

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:06.480
So what I want to do
is create the space

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:10.290
so that the things that we
already know are problematic

00:18:10.290 --> 00:18:11.580
are certainly present.

00:18:11.580 --> 00:18:16.380
But they don't define what
becomes possible between us.

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:18.810
In my interviews--
when you just asked me

00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:23.200
that, intuitively, what comes
to mind is, I get excited.

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:27.780
I'm just excited about
the conversation.

00:18:27.780 --> 00:18:33.340
And I want to prepare
because I want

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:38.440
them to be able to relax as
quickly as possible so that we

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:40.540
can really go deep.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:47.680
And one way I do that is by
knowing about them, by honoring

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:51.310
them, by reading their books
if they've written books,

00:18:51.310 --> 00:18:54.890
or knowing what they do.

00:18:54.890 --> 00:18:56.030
I do a lot of--

00:18:56.030 --> 00:18:58.330
I will also read other
interviews they've given.

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:03.820
I would say-- so I think of
my interview preparation mode

00:19:03.820 --> 00:19:09.190
as the Vulcan mind-meld mode
of interview preparation,

00:19:09.190 --> 00:19:11.590
you know?

00:19:11.590 --> 00:19:13.900
My mind, your mind, your
thoughts to my thoughts--

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:17.620
because my goal in
preparing is not

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:24.580
that I know what they think
as much as how they think.

00:19:27.250 --> 00:19:30.400
And again, this works if they're
halfway across the world,

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:33.000
and I'm in a studio,
and they're in a studio.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.750
That, we all know what
this experience is,

00:19:34.750 --> 00:19:40.870
if you meet someone new,
and you know very quickly

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:45.730
if you're going to have to
explain yourself, defend

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:48.280
yourself, be on guard.

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:52.870
And then that's what your
whole body gears up to do.

00:19:52.870 --> 00:19:55.000
And then that just--

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.600
then you're off.

00:19:56.600 --> 00:19:58.600
But what I'm aiming for
is this other experience

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:02.260
we have all also had
where you meet somebody,

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:05.950
and you just know
that they get you.

00:20:05.950 --> 00:20:08.170
And even when I say
that to you right now,

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:15.130
my body relaxes, and there
is a lot more possibility.

00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:17.540
And it's a soft--

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:18.040
right?

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.980
It's a soft space in which
just more can happen.

00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:24.220
And I think it's a more
playful adventurous

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:25.970
space for the same reason.

00:20:25.970 --> 00:20:27.590
DANIELLE KRETTEK: I interrupted
you with my question, so--

00:20:27.590 --> 00:20:28.180
KRISTA TIPPETT: No, no.

00:20:28.180 --> 00:20:28.679
I love that.

00:20:28.679 --> 00:20:30.159
DANIELLE KRETTEK: So please--

00:20:30.159 --> 00:20:31.450
KRISTA TIPPETT: I did want to--

00:20:35.599 --> 00:20:38.550
one of the things you said
to me is that you also

00:20:38.550 --> 00:20:41.760
wanted to invite me here
at Google to just say

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:45.610
whatever was on my mind that
I would want to say and--

00:20:45.610 --> 00:20:49.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:49.980
--to you.

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:54.790
And actually, I have a fair
number of conversations,

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:57.390
not about technology, per
se, but about our lives

00:20:57.390 --> 00:21:04.000
with technology and do think
about this a great deal.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.850
And one thing I want
to say is that--

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:11.360
and I know you all are--

00:21:11.360 --> 00:21:14.960
we're now having this kind
of reckoning, culturally,

00:21:14.960 --> 00:21:19.070
with the civilizational
effect of the work you

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:22.210
do, the work that
happens in this industry.

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:24.980
And we've all created that
civilizational effect.

00:21:24.980 --> 00:21:26.690
We've all co-created it.

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:28.580
And it's so new.

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:32.160
And these technologies are
so much in their infancy.

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:34.560
And I think one of the
messages that's come through so

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:36.870
clearly is--

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:38.790
with wise people in
my conversations--

00:21:38.790 --> 00:21:43.050
is that we forget that all
of this is in its infancy

00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:44.520
because it is so powerful.

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.080
And it has so quickly--

00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:48.780
feels like-- taken
over our lives.

00:21:48.780 --> 00:21:50.700
But there is the opportunity.

00:21:50.700 --> 00:21:54.480
And the challenge is
to shape our lives

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:58.710
with technology and the
technologies to human purpose.

00:21:58.710 --> 00:22:02.440
And I'm also aware of--

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:05.830
I do think-- this is
also true in journalism.

00:22:05.830 --> 00:22:08.950
Culturally, we're
so much more skilled

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:11.530
at sophisticated analysis
and criticism of what

00:22:11.530 --> 00:22:17.440
is flawed and failing and
destructive and terrifying and

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:19.120
catastrophic.

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:21.700
We're really good at that.

00:22:21.700 --> 00:22:29.090
And we're not as sophisticated
at seeing and analyzing

00:22:29.090 --> 00:22:33.150
and working with and,
thereby, nurturing

00:22:33.150 --> 00:22:37.870
what is generative and
beautiful and humane.

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:40.320
And I think that you--

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:42.870
I know you know this.

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:46.620
There's so much that is
human and beautiful, humane

00:22:46.620 --> 00:22:53.070
and generative, in our lives
with technology as well.

00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:55.200
I would just say one
of the things that's

00:22:55.200 --> 00:23:02.940
so clear to me in the sphere I'm
in is the abundance of poetry

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:07.380
that has this whole
new life online

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:12.720
and how people are making
poetry and putting it up there

00:23:12.720 --> 00:23:16.180
and sharing it.

00:23:16.180 --> 00:23:20.050
And I think this is also
a civilizational move.

00:23:20.050 --> 00:23:22.390
Poetry does, in fact,
in human societies,

00:23:22.390 --> 00:23:24.940
rise up when we are
in these moments

00:23:24.940 --> 00:23:26.515
of cultural and
political disarray.

00:23:26.515 --> 00:23:27.115
It does.

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:34.640
It's something we are turning
to as our official forms

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:40.790
of language and discourse are so
broken and failing us so badly.

00:23:40.790 --> 00:23:47.240
And it gives us ways to give
voice to the best of ourselves.

00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:52.340
And actually, also, it gives
us ways to put questions

00:23:52.340 --> 00:23:53.430
into the room--

00:23:53.430 --> 00:23:56.360
and I mean "the room" in
a very expansive sense,

00:23:56.360 --> 00:23:57.380
the public room--

00:24:00.110 --> 00:24:04.130
that are there for us to live
rather than answer or fight

00:24:04.130 --> 00:24:04.630
about.

00:24:07.970 --> 00:24:11.650
And one of those
questions, by way

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:13.240
of poetry, that
I work with a lot

00:24:13.240 --> 00:24:17.860
is from Elizabeth Alexander, who
was the poet of the first Obama

00:24:17.860 --> 00:24:18.790
administration.

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:22.540
And she has this
poem, which ends,

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:25.480
"Poetry is the human voice.

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:30.220
And are we not of
interest to each other?"

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:34.840
To me, that is a question
that reframes, like,

00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:35.830
can we get along?

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:38.080
Or are you a Republican
or a Democrat?

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:39.850
That's a question
that could help

00:24:39.850 --> 00:24:42.100
reframe our grappling
with all the things we

00:24:42.100 --> 00:24:44.120
want to grapple with.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:47.290
And then I'm sure many of you
are aware that Mary Oliver died

00:24:47.290 --> 00:24:48.100
last week.

00:24:48.100 --> 00:24:51.460
And I was so
privileged to have, I

00:24:51.460 --> 00:24:52.900
think, the last
big interview she

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:57.370
gave in 2015 in
which, I will share,

00:24:57.370 --> 00:24:59.560
she smoked the entire time.

00:24:59.560 --> 00:25:00.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:00.490 --> 00:25:02.530
It's the only
interview I've ever

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:07.450
had where my producer texted
me before I arrived and said,

00:25:07.450 --> 00:25:09.266
she wants to smoke,
are you OK with that?

00:25:09.266 --> 00:25:10.890
I was like, she never
gives interviews.

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:12.056
Of course, I'm OK with that.

00:25:12.056 --> 00:25:15.070
But it was so perfect.

00:25:15.070 --> 00:25:15.785
Because--

00:25:15.785 --> 00:25:17.360
DANIELLE KRETTEK: And you
were in the room for this one?

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:17.800
KRISTA TIPPETT: What?

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:19.010
DANIELLE KRETTEK: It
wasn't remote smoking.

00:25:19.010 --> 00:25:19.670
It was in the room.

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:20.470
KRISTA TIPPETT: No,
we were in the room.

00:25:20.470 --> 00:25:21.580
It was in my face.

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:23.050
And I was privileged.

00:25:23.050 --> 00:25:25.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:25.050 --> 00:25:27.340
And she was wearing a New
England Patriots sweatshirt.

00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:30.670
And it was just-- it made her
so much more perfect that she's

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:32.050
so three-dimensional.

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:33.490
Because you know Mary Oliver--

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:36.301
her critics think that
she's like poetry-lite,

00:25:36.301 --> 00:25:38.800
because she writes beautiful
things about the natural world.

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:43.780
And I think some of the
people who love her most

00:25:43.780 --> 00:25:46.000
put her up on a pedestal
and turn her into a saint.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.870
And the truth is, if you think
about a sophisticated analysis

00:25:49.870 --> 00:25:53.950
of goodness and beauty,
she fled to the woods

00:25:53.950 --> 00:25:56.980
and started writing
poetry because she was

00:25:56.980 --> 00:26:00.970
living in an abusive household.

00:26:00.970 --> 00:26:06.220
And the poet-- she spent
years, in young adulthood,

00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:11.180
gathering berries because
that's what she had to eat.

00:26:11.180 --> 00:26:14.320
And it was that
three-dimensionality of her--

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:17.830
and that's what gives her
poems about beauty and goodness

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:18.670
such heft.

00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:20.050
And actually, I took--

00:26:20.050 --> 00:26:23.120
so here, a question she
put out into the world

00:26:23.120 --> 00:26:25.340
that is now rippling
through it again--

00:26:25.340 --> 00:26:27.310
and it's one of these
transformative questions

00:26:27.310 --> 00:26:28.780
we can live--

00:26:28.780 --> 00:26:32.050
tell me, what is it you
plan to do with your one

00:26:32.050 --> 00:26:35.520
wild and precious life?

00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:39.390
And another gift she gave
me and that interview was--

00:26:39.390 --> 00:26:41.500
to just bring this to a close--

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:44.190
is the phrase--

00:26:44.190 --> 00:26:45.820
I like the phrase,
generous listening.

00:26:45.820 --> 00:26:49.660
Mary Oliver used the
phrase, convivial listening.

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:52.494
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Hmm-- there's
like a bubbling in that.

00:26:52.494 --> 00:26:53.410
KRISTA TIPPETT: It's--

00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:54.300
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
--that's really lovely--

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:55.130
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:26:55.130 --> 00:26:57.020
DANIELLE KRETTEK: --being
the poetess that she is.

00:26:57.020 --> 00:26:58.390
I'm glad you brought Mary up.

00:26:58.390 --> 00:27:00.867
Because actually,
when I saw that,

00:27:00.867 --> 00:27:02.450
I thought immediately
of you because I

00:27:02.450 --> 00:27:03.680
listened to that interview.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:07.100
And the thing that touched
me the most in that interview

00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:10.040
with Mary was how she
talked about her poetry

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:13.380
being a moving thing--
that she would walk to have

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:14.630
the poetry coming through her.

00:27:14.630 --> 00:27:16.504
And then she'd have to
run home and get the--

00:27:16.504 --> 00:27:19.190
and what I loved about
that was just that it

00:27:19.190 --> 00:27:20.930
was the living the questions.

00:27:20.930 --> 00:27:23.589
It isn't the-- I sit down, and
[? these ?] things comes to us.

00:27:23.589 --> 00:27:25.880
And I think something that
you were talking about a few

00:27:25.880 --> 00:27:29.690
minutes ago with journalism--
which is the nature

00:27:29.690 --> 00:27:33.290
of the questions-- again, you
can go so easily to the places

00:27:33.290 --> 00:27:34.760
of--

00:27:34.760 --> 00:27:38.762
the darker spaces, the shadowy
spaces because it works.

00:27:38.762 --> 00:27:40.470
There's a lot of edge
there to work with.

00:27:40.470 --> 00:27:43.760
I think design and journalism
is very similar, in terms of,

00:27:43.760 --> 00:27:46.280
there's a curiosity.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:46.790
It's funny.

00:27:46.790 --> 00:27:48.680
You can almost say--

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:53.900
search poetry and replace design
or art or all these things.

00:27:53.900 --> 00:27:57.272
It's all inquiry into that
thing at the core of something

00:27:57.272 --> 00:27:59.480
that you're going to bring
out and make felt and move

00:27:59.480 --> 00:28:00.670
everything else away.

00:28:00.670 --> 00:28:02.540
And when I look at
design or journalism,

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:04.190
I think about this
deep curiosity

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:05.660
that rises up into us.

00:28:05.660 --> 00:28:09.250
And do we want to just look for
the problems we want to solve,

00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:11.090
the itchy seams
that drive us crazy

00:28:11.090 --> 00:28:13.100
or the things that feel
like they're not right?

00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:15.080
Or is there actually
something even deeper

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:18.650
than that that's more
unifying than that that

00:28:18.650 --> 00:28:20.000
is this place of beauty?

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.700
And the way you
describe beauty is--

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:25.470
actually, I don't want to
misquote you right here.

00:28:25.470 --> 00:28:30.020
So let me make sure
that I get this right.

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:32.270
In my notes, I literally
have the [? hippiest ?] quote

00:28:32.270 --> 00:28:35.270
on beauty, which is always
my touchstone, which

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:37.420
is, "The world is
hopelessly reeling.

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:40.070
Stay close to the sounds
that bring you alive."

00:28:40.070 --> 00:28:43.820
And your quote is, "Beauty is
that, in the presence of which,

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:45.160
we feel more alive."

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:45.510
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:28:45.510 --> 00:28:46.700
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
So this vitality

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:47.840
you're speaking about--

00:28:47.840 --> 00:28:48.715
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:28:48.715 --> 00:28:51.170
And that's actually a
language of John O'Donohue,

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:56.610
who is another poet and
theologian and philosopher.

00:28:56.610 --> 00:28:59.960
And so he was talking--

00:28:59.960 --> 00:29:05.060
we were actually
talking about how

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:08.960
a lot of the words that we need
the most and love the most also

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:09.485
get ruined.

00:29:12.790 --> 00:29:17.300
And I think that's true of words
like peace and justice and love

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:18.510
and kindness.

00:29:18.510 --> 00:29:22.870
They get on bumper stickers, or
they get partisan affiliations.

00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:27.140
And so I think sometimes we
have to put them to one side,

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:29.720
and use them less, and
say what we're saying,

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:33.830
and use a universe of words,
and not expect those words to do

00:29:33.830 --> 00:29:35.790
the work for us.

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:37.890
But sometimes we just
really have to claim a word

00:29:37.890 --> 00:29:38.390
and say, no.

00:29:38.390 --> 00:29:39.723
We're not going to let this die.

00:29:39.723 --> 00:29:40.800
We have to resurrect it.

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:43.640
And I'm trying to do that
with the word "civility."

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:45.560
But he used the word "beauty."

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:51.830
And I said to him, well, beauty
is another one of those words.

00:29:51.830 --> 00:29:53.420
I said, if you
just threw the word

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:56.930
"beauty" into many
conversations, maybe

00:29:56.930 --> 00:30:01.430
where my mind would go is to
the flawless face on the cover

00:30:01.430 --> 00:30:03.350
of a magazine, right?

00:30:03.350 --> 00:30:04.760
And he said, no, no.

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:06.075
That's glamor.

00:30:06.075 --> 00:30:11.330
And he said, beauty is that,
in the presence of which,

00:30:11.330 --> 00:30:12.680
we feel more alive.

00:30:15.530 --> 00:30:23.480
And what you just said
about the inquiry--

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:25.720
if we're focused on
solving the problems,

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:29.210
do we then end up orienting
towards the problems?

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:36.560
And I don't think we have
to do one or the other.

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:41.210
I think we do, to some extent,
need to focus on the problems.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:46.530
And it's also just as
serious and robust a question

00:30:46.530 --> 00:30:50.930
to ask, what do
we want to amplify

00:30:50.930 --> 00:30:53.500
because it is good for us?

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:54.500
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Mm-hm.

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:57.440
KRISTA TIPPETT: Because
it speaks to and elicits

00:30:57.440 --> 00:31:02.150
the best of which our
species is capable.

00:31:02.150 --> 00:31:04.650
DANIELLE KRETTEK: I think that
so much of the conversation--

00:31:04.650 --> 00:31:06.015
to speak for Google.

00:31:06.015 --> 00:31:08.040
No, to speak for
myself and as part

00:31:08.040 --> 00:31:09.870
of the community of Google--

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:13.060
I think that's part of what's
so fascinating about this braces

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:16.110
phase, awkward adolescent
moment we are in with technology

00:31:16.110 --> 00:31:16.680
right now.

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:16.800
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:31:16.800 --> 00:31:18.091
DANIELLE KRETTEK: You're right.

00:31:18.091 --> 00:31:21.100
The power is what has brought
us along so far, so fast.

00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:22.750
But there's so much
more to be done.

00:31:22.750 --> 00:31:23.990
There's so much expansion.

00:31:23.990 --> 00:31:24.990
There's so much support.

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:26.610
There's so much positivity.

00:31:26.610 --> 00:31:29.580
It's easy to focus on the fear
part of it because that's real,

00:31:29.580 --> 00:31:32.190
and that's happening,
and things must shift.

00:31:32.190 --> 00:31:35.250
But there's so much
potential if you focus on,

00:31:35.250 --> 00:31:37.620
what are the things that we
want to expand in people?

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:39.270
What are the ways
we can support?

00:31:39.270 --> 00:31:41.850
How can we look, not just at
the functional and productive

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:45.110
needs, but at the generative,
spacious needs of people?

00:31:45.110 --> 00:31:47.500
How is the whole person welcome?

00:31:47.500 --> 00:31:50.160
And I think, what's so curious
and part of why this listening

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:52.860
conversation-- it's so wonderful
to have everyone in the room

00:31:52.860 --> 00:31:53.700
here--

00:31:53.700 --> 00:31:58.440
is we are really trying to go
back to these core skills that

00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:02.400
are so easy to forget with the
speed with which we all live

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:06.210
and remember, what does it
mean to, in our process,

00:32:06.210 --> 00:32:08.730
open up moments
where we have spaces

00:32:08.730 --> 00:32:12.090
for better listening, where
we are practicing some

00:32:12.090 --> 00:32:14.640
of these skills in
a different way,

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:19.680
working with the design process
so that it's not the normal way

00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:20.730
that we make things?

00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:22.470
But that we ourselves--

00:32:22.470 --> 00:32:25.500
more of us is welcome in that
room and at the whiteboard--

00:32:25.500 --> 00:32:28.890
that there is, for the humans
on this side and the way that it

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:32.640
touches people on the outside,
and the way that all circles--

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:35.670
what does it mean to
work with new models

00:32:35.670 --> 00:32:38.730
and open spaces in these
places that we all create in?

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:40.190
KRISTA TIPPETT:
That's also where--

00:32:40.190 --> 00:32:41.814
you think about that
as an intersection

00:32:41.814 --> 00:32:44.330
of design and the
hospitality virtue, right?

00:32:44.330 --> 00:32:47.540
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
Mm-mm, absolutely.

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:50.080
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:32:50.080 --> 00:33:00.410
I'm very clear that, as much
as we are, again, seeing the--

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:02.324
well, we're seeing the
dark side of ourselves

00:33:02.324 --> 00:33:03.365
on this great big canvas.

00:33:05.990 --> 00:33:12.019
And we're seeing this very
young industry, which--

00:33:12.019 --> 00:33:13.560
one of the things
I've learned here--

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:16.060
is it's not really an industry.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:18.514
It's a bunch of companies
competing with each other.

00:33:18.514 --> 00:33:20.805
But the world actually needs
you all to be an industry.

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:31.660
This industry-- I spent
my 20s in divided Berlin.

00:33:31.660 --> 00:33:35.590
And I keep thinking
about it this out here

00:33:35.590 --> 00:33:36.370
in Silicon Valley.

00:33:36.370 --> 00:33:40.260
Because as much
as we are riveted

00:33:40.260 --> 00:33:42.540
by what's happening
in Washington, DC

00:33:42.540 --> 00:33:49.200
or in London, your company--

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:51.725
these companies are the
superpowers of this century.

00:33:54.590 --> 00:33:55.840
And that's huge.

00:33:55.840 --> 00:33:57.940
And we're all now
aware of the perils

00:33:57.940 --> 00:33:59.800
of that and all the
pieces that need

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:01.870
to be in place for
that to be true

00:34:01.870 --> 00:34:03.480
and to be good for humanity.

00:34:03.480 --> 00:34:07.160
But I also see that--

00:34:11.460 --> 00:34:15.130
every generation,
every century has

00:34:15.130 --> 00:34:18.730
had its life-altering
technologies, right?

00:34:18.730 --> 00:34:20.925
The railroad changed everything.

00:34:20.925 --> 00:34:22.300
The telephone
changed everything.

00:34:22.300 --> 00:34:23.591
Electricity changed everything.

00:34:23.591 --> 00:34:26.100
Fire changed everything.

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:30.230
But what is new about
our technologies--

00:34:30.230 --> 00:34:31.701
of course, the
pace is different.

00:34:31.701 --> 00:34:33.159
But I don't think
that's really it.

00:34:33.159 --> 00:34:35.350
Because I think, in
other generations,

00:34:35.350 --> 00:34:38.889
the pace of those things
was equally completely

00:34:38.889 --> 00:34:40.540
disorienting.

00:34:40.540 --> 00:34:43.870
It is the intimacy.

00:34:43.870 --> 00:34:50.050
Our technologies are woven
into the fabric of our days,

00:34:50.050 --> 00:34:51.770
into the fabric of our lives.

00:34:51.770 --> 00:34:58.150
They are shifting the way
we make and lead and learn

00:34:58.150 --> 00:35:00.420
and love.

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:06.320
They are woven into
the human enterprise.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:11.750
And what I also see is
that these technologies,

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:15.620
and the interconnected world
and economies they've given us,

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:18.350
have actually
given us the tools,

00:35:18.350 --> 00:35:25.670
for the first time as a species,
to think and act as a species.

00:35:25.670 --> 00:35:29.030
We are not anywhere living
up to that right now.

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:30.870
That's not the picture.

00:35:30.870 --> 00:35:33.270
But this is the reality.

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:36.410
This is the potential.

00:35:36.410 --> 00:35:38.610
DANIELLE KRETTEK: I love
that articulation of it.

00:35:38.610 --> 00:35:40.320
I've never heard
it quite like that.

00:35:40.320 --> 00:35:42.720
But indeed, it is--

00:35:42.720 --> 00:35:45.740
yeah-- the ability
to be interconnected.

00:35:45.740 --> 00:35:48.320
When you say, woven,
it's interconnected,

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:51.950
not just in our humanity,
but actually in the way

00:35:51.950 --> 00:35:53.282
that we are connected.

00:35:53.282 --> 00:35:53.990
And I think the--

00:35:53.990 --> 00:35:54.440
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:35:54.440 --> 00:35:55.640
Inside and outside.

00:35:55.640 --> 00:35:56.720
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Yes.

00:35:56.720 --> 00:35:59.100
That inner and outer
is so critical.

00:35:59.100 --> 00:36:01.250
And actually, it's perfect
that you said that.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:04.562
Because there was a
moment that you had,

00:36:04.562 --> 00:36:06.020
that you reflected
on in your book,

00:36:06.020 --> 00:36:08.240
with Dr. Rachel
Naomi Remen where

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:10.179
you talk about tikkan olam.

00:36:10.179 --> 00:36:11.720
And what's interesting
is, I actually

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:13.610
had a moment where I
was like, [GASP] shall

00:36:13.610 --> 00:36:16.230
I talk about
spirituality at Google?

00:36:16.230 --> 00:36:18.107
And I was like, absolutely, yes.

00:36:18.107 --> 00:36:19.940
This is the human heart
we're talking about.

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:21.290
The language is almost--

00:36:21.290 --> 00:36:24.040
you can use whatever
language you want.

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:26.270
The thing that we were
speaking about, the thing that

00:36:26.270 --> 00:36:28.728
breaks all of our hearts, the
thing that connects all of us

00:36:28.728 --> 00:36:29.730
is always the same.

00:36:29.730 --> 00:36:31.130
So that is what this is.

00:36:31.130 --> 00:36:33.830
"But sometime early in
the life of the world,

00:36:33.830 --> 00:36:36.584
something happened to shatter"--
you know, this origin myth--

00:36:36.584 --> 00:36:38.750
"the light of the universe
and the countless pieces.

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:41.630
They lodged as sparks in
every part of creation.

00:36:41.630 --> 00:36:43.880
Our highest human
calling is to help repair

00:36:43.880 --> 00:36:48.140
the part of the world that
we can see and touch."

00:36:48.140 --> 00:36:51.620
And I just immediately thought,
what if everything we designed

00:36:51.620 --> 00:36:53.930
had that beauty and service--

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:55.730
and your version of beauty--

00:36:55.730 --> 00:36:58.070
you and John's-- to it?

00:36:58.070 --> 00:37:00.830
This idea that we can repair
the parts of the world

00:37:00.830 --> 00:37:04.670
that we see and touch, that is
a pretty incredible fabric when

00:37:04.670 --> 00:37:08.220
we think about what filament is
at our fingers here at Google.

00:37:08.220 --> 00:37:11.840
What a great mission to
organize and organize

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:13.970
the world's information,
to light it up

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:15.120
and repair it as well.

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:15.630
I think that's
where we're moving.

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:16.220
KRISTA TIPPETT: And
you know what's else?

00:37:16.220 --> 00:37:19.160
It's also, at the one and
the same time, it's audacious

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:20.890
and it's doable.

00:37:20.890 --> 00:37:23.990
Because that's the Jewish--

00:37:23.990 --> 00:37:25.560
the story behind the--

00:37:25.560 --> 00:37:28.140
it's called "The
Birthday of the World."

00:37:28.140 --> 00:37:30.980
And it's behind the
moral commandment

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:32.314
to repair the world.

00:37:32.314 --> 00:37:34.730
And I really love-- like,
that's another piece of language

00:37:34.730 --> 00:37:36.320
that I think is so useful.

00:37:36.320 --> 00:37:38.750
It's so much better
than "save the world,"

00:37:38.750 --> 00:37:41.390
which was what the
20th century was about.

00:37:41.390 --> 00:37:44.810
And so much damage was done in
the name of "saving the world."

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:46.310
And it also made people--

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:50.810
it actually alienated people
from their sense of agency.

00:37:50.810 --> 00:37:53.420
But repair the world--

00:37:53.420 --> 00:37:57.320
and you know, ever
since 2016, it's just--

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:59.330
all the images that
come to mind about what

00:37:59.330 --> 00:38:01.430
we have to do in our country--

00:38:01.430 --> 00:38:07.800
it's weaving, stitching, it's
all these-- mending, repairing.

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:09.370
And the thing is,
it's a big picture.

00:38:09.370 --> 00:38:11.790
But it's one
relationship at a time.

00:38:11.790 --> 00:38:13.550
And that's what she said too.

00:38:13.550 --> 00:38:19.150
Repair the world is the
highest human calling.

00:38:19.150 --> 00:38:21.900
But you start with what
you can see and touch.

00:38:21.900 --> 00:38:24.237
That's what you're called to.

00:38:24.237 --> 00:38:25.320
DANIELLE KRETTEK: I just--

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:26.890
I love that pragmatism.

00:38:26.890 --> 00:38:30.070
And also, what I feel
like is rising up in

00:38:30.070 --> 00:38:32.920
the conversation too is this--

00:38:32.920 --> 00:38:33.870
save the world.

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:35.320
It made me think.

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:38.660
There is this really beautiful
intention we have in the Valley

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:40.430
and in technology.

00:38:40.430 --> 00:38:42.850
How can we solve these
audacious human problems--

00:38:42.850 --> 00:38:44.810
these large-scale
massive things?

00:38:44.810 --> 00:38:48.070
How can we-- the intention
of that is so beautiful.

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:51.490
The results of that
are not always.

00:38:51.490 --> 00:38:53.825
When you speak about
intentionality and hospitality

00:38:53.825 --> 00:38:55.450
and this whole space
that we've started

00:38:55.450 --> 00:39:00.160
to unroll in our conversation,
what's your advice for us

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:02.875
with that?

00:39:02.875 --> 00:39:06.550
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah,
well, that's all.

00:39:06.550 --> 00:39:08.110
I'm going to now
solve it for you.

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:10.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:10.360 --> 00:39:13.810
But what I will say, I
think the intentionality--

00:39:13.810 --> 00:39:14.876
your question is so good.

00:39:14.876 --> 00:39:16.500
You know, that's my
highest compliment.

00:39:16.500 --> 00:39:17.560
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Aw!

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:19.180
KRISTA TIPPETT: That--

00:39:19.180 --> 00:39:20.680
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
It is my birthday.

