our arms around

00:40:17.020 --> 00:40:19.220
these big civilizational--

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:21.580
these intimate and
civilizational challenges

00:40:21.580 --> 00:40:22.180
we have--

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:27.790
and the problem is,
as we also know,

00:40:27.790 --> 00:40:32.370
if you rush to do something--

00:40:32.370 --> 00:40:37.830
if you rush to a solution,
you often waste time.

00:40:37.830 --> 00:40:42.040
You often end up
setting something loose

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:45.540
that didn't have the
intentionality that it needed,

00:40:45.540 --> 00:40:50.040
that you then spend time
rolling back and dismantling

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.120
and solving for.

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:59.890
Which is all by way of saying,
it would behoove us now--

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:02.110
and I mean, in every
aspect of our lives

00:41:02.110 --> 00:41:04.570
and in everything we do,
whatever our work is--

00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:12.500
because this is a
critical moment--

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:22.690
to really invest our time,
our creativity, our attention,

00:41:22.690 --> 00:41:26.980
the sophistication we would
give to solving a problem

00:41:26.980 --> 00:41:31.120
to the why and the how of it.

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:36.140
Yeah.

00:41:36.140 --> 00:41:38.410
And what that means--

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:43.280
but that has some trade-offs
that are culturally difficult,

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:44.000
right?

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.100
That means you would
spend a lot more time

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:49.790
on something that doesn't
look like you're being busy.

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:52.650
So there's a culture shift
that has to happen around this.

00:41:52.650 --> 00:41:57.679
A language I love that actually
comes from spiritual traditions

00:41:57.679 --> 00:41:58.970
is the language of discernment.

00:41:58.970 --> 00:42:00.136
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Mm, mm-hm.

00:42:04.759 --> 00:42:06.800
KRISTA TIPPETT: I know
these industries you're in

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:08.030
are all about innovation.

00:42:08.030 --> 00:42:10.760
And we actually have
to hoist in that a lot

00:42:10.760 --> 00:42:15.200
of the massive problems
we're dealing with now

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:18.380
are the result of innovations.

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:24.160
Like, what we did with
food 50 years ago,

00:42:24.160 --> 00:42:25.870
where we created convenience--

00:42:29.380 --> 00:42:30.850
do you know what
an innovation it

00:42:30.850 --> 00:42:35.230
was to have food coming
out of boxes and cans?

00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:39.070
Life-changing, amazing--
so bad for us--

00:42:39.070 --> 00:42:46.660
very lucrative-- so bad for us.

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:51.310
And then our government
policies followed it.

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:53.170
Agriculture followed it.

00:42:53.170 --> 00:42:54.590
All of these things followed it.

00:42:54.590 --> 00:42:59.320
But now we're implicated in
this massive complex of things

00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:03.040
around climate and
health and economies

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.440
that we have to take apart
and solve for, right?

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:10.240
So innovation is not,
in itself, a good.

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:12.280
Innovation is not
necessarily progress.

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:14.950
And so that's
something to ponder.

00:43:14.950 --> 00:43:17.750
And I think, if you say--

00:43:17.750 --> 00:43:20.470
if our technologies and
our lives with them are

00:43:20.470 --> 00:43:24.130
in our adolescence, if these
super-power companies are also

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:25.990
very young--

00:43:25.990 --> 00:43:27.940
I think that
discernment muscle--

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:30.160
of course, innovation
has been a core value--

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:34.960
but in the next stage, asking,
will it be good for the world?

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:36.410
Will it be good for humanity?

00:43:36.410 --> 00:43:39.040
And that's going to
look like wasting time--

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:40.600
being discerning.

00:43:40.600 --> 00:43:42.850
DANIELLE KRETTEK: You use
the word, imagination, a lot

00:43:42.850 --> 00:43:44.892
to describe that
generative, spacious process

00:43:44.892 --> 00:43:45.600
in the beginning.

00:43:45.600 --> 00:43:45.700
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:47.440
DANIELLE KRETTEK: And I think
imagination and discernment

00:43:47.440 --> 00:43:49.810
go really beautifully
together towards that.

00:43:49.810 --> 00:43:52.840
I must pick up-- so you
mentioned that civility is

00:43:52.840 --> 00:43:55.321
a word that means a lot to
you now and just talking about

00:43:55.321 --> 00:43:55.820
these--

00:43:55.820 --> 00:43:58.270
I love saying that these are
civilization-level problems

00:43:58.270 --> 00:44:01.000
because it includes the
humanity and the culture

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.610
and just all things at once.

00:44:03.610 --> 00:44:05.590
Please share your
definition [? now-- ?]

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:06.923
KRISTA TIPPETT: Oh, of civility?

00:44:06.923 --> 00:44:08.812
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Yes.

00:44:08.812 --> 00:44:11.020
KRISTA TIPPETT: Well, I know
it's a problematic word.

00:44:11.020 --> 00:44:13.030
And I always add
other adjectives.

00:44:13.030 --> 00:44:16.600
Like, I say, adventurous
civility or muscular civility.

00:44:23.190 --> 00:44:27.120
I think we have to get
past the idea that--

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:28.230
to me, it's not--

00:44:28.230 --> 00:44:29.370
again, what is it not?

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:32.280
It's not being nice,
kind, polite, and tame.

00:44:36.030 --> 00:44:41.550
Those aren't big enough
qualities to meet this moment.

00:44:41.550 --> 00:44:43.570
I'm not saying there's
not a place for them.

00:44:43.570 --> 00:44:45.850
But that's not what
civility is about.

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:51.510
I want to say that civility,
that the intentionality

00:44:51.510 --> 00:44:54.405
behind it is this repair
of our life together.

00:44:59.960 --> 00:45:10.140
I think the questions that have
been with humanity and animated

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:13.950
humanity and, I
think animated us

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:16.590
at our best, that are
ancient and enduring are,

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:17.910
what does it mean to be human?

00:45:17.910 --> 00:45:19.035
And how do we want to live?

00:45:21.750 --> 00:45:26.770
And the third question is,
who will we be to each other?

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:29.590
And that question,
across history,

00:45:29.590 --> 00:45:32.420
has been optional
in many settings.

00:45:32.420 --> 00:45:34.420
And I think, actually,
the technologies

00:45:34.420 --> 00:45:39.330
you've created make that
question inextricable now

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:42.340
for humans--

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:45.560
inextricable from the question
of what it means to be human

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:47.092
and how we want to live.

00:45:47.092 --> 00:45:48.300
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Absolutely.

00:45:48.300 --> 00:45:51.970
KRISTA TIPPETT: And
civility, in my mind--

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:54.700
we're also-- there's so
many different things

00:45:54.700 --> 00:45:56.440
happening at once,
which is part of what

00:45:56.440 --> 00:45:57.620
makes this moment dizzying.

00:45:57.620 --> 00:45:59.620
And we're very focused
on what's going wrong.

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:03.810
But there are so
many ways that we're

00:46:03.810 --> 00:46:07.530
understanding the fullness
of what it means to be human

00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:11.700
and understanding our
bodies and our brains

00:46:11.700 --> 00:46:14.250
and the interaction
between them.

00:46:14.250 --> 00:46:21.370
And also, in culture--

00:46:21.370 --> 00:46:26.290
fitfully, imperfectly,
too slowly, but--

00:46:26.290 --> 00:46:30.360
but-- gaining a sense
of the fullness of--

00:46:33.090 --> 00:46:34.410
what is-- I want--

00:46:34.410 --> 00:46:37.740
I think these words like
diversity and tolerance

00:46:37.740 --> 00:46:40.310
are way too small.

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.330
Inclusion-- still,
there's an in-circle.

00:46:43.330 --> 00:46:45.180
But I think we're really
moving beyond this.

00:46:45.180 --> 00:46:47.760
We want the full
array of humanity

00:46:47.760 --> 00:46:50.470
in the room to have its place.

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:55.560
We have such a newly
robust understanding

00:46:55.560 --> 00:46:58.140
just of the matter of identity.

00:46:58.140 --> 00:47:01.035
We are the generation
that is redefining gender.

00:47:04.750 --> 00:47:10.160
So I think one of the things
that happened with the notion

00:47:10.160 --> 00:47:13.220
of civility was that it was
about-- like, these phrases--

00:47:13.220 --> 00:47:17.420
like, we would all
get on this same page.

00:47:17.420 --> 00:47:19.790
Or the thing we do-- like,
the democratic instinct.

00:47:19.790 --> 00:47:22.456
Well, you've got some people who
think that it's something like,

00:47:22.456 --> 00:47:25.130
take a vote, and move on.

00:47:25.130 --> 00:47:28.640
But these intimate
civilizational questions

00:47:28.640 --> 00:47:31.850
of how we're going to live,
we all have a stake in them.

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:34.430
So to me, civility,
in this generation,

00:47:34.430 --> 00:47:37.400
is about knowing that
we walk into the room

00:47:37.400 --> 00:47:40.910
or into the discussion with
deep, profound differences

00:47:40.910 --> 00:47:43.200
that are meaningful
and important to us.

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:45.690
And the point is not agreeing.

00:47:49.450 --> 00:47:51.970
The point is getting
into a relationship.

00:47:51.970 --> 00:47:54.860
The point is coming
to know each other.

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:57.490
And that thing of
opening up what is--

00:47:57.490 --> 00:47:59.500
not letting those
things we disagree

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:02.590
on define what is possible
between us-- opening up

00:48:02.590 --> 00:48:07.000
a new space where, perhaps,
what we have in common are

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:08.050
our questions.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:09.660
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Absolutely.

00:48:09.660 --> 00:48:10.160
Yeah.

00:48:10.160 --> 00:48:11.950
And that opening
of the space that's

00:48:11.950 --> 00:48:14.080
bigger than the
differences that allows

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:17.350
for all of the questions,
all of the voices--

00:48:17.350 --> 00:48:20.680
something that you were
speaking with Pico Iyer

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:23.680
about in that recent
interview was how he

00:48:23.680 --> 00:48:25.450
talked about how-- what was it?

00:48:25.450 --> 00:48:26.955
In the institutions
of skepticism--

00:48:26.955 --> 00:48:29.560
he's gone to all these
incredibly decorated

00:48:29.560 --> 00:48:31.870
universities, which
he refers to as

00:48:31.870 --> 00:48:33.630
the institutions of skepticism.

00:48:33.630 --> 00:48:37.510
And he says that we learned how
to talk, but not how to listen,

00:48:37.510 --> 00:48:39.940
how to put ourselves
forward, but not

00:48:39.940 --> 00:48:42.250
how to actually erase ourselves.

00:48:42.250 --> 00:48:45.195
And so much of that is this--
the living of the listening,

00:48:45.195 --> 00:48:47.350
the living of the questions.

00:48:47.350 --> 00:48:49.810
If we do that in an
artful way, there really

00:48:49.810 --> 00:48:51.880
is space for all of that.

00:48:51.880 --> 00:48:54.077
Whereas, the way
currently it works,

00:48:54.077 --> 00:48:55.660
maybe there isn't
always space for it.

00:48:55.660 --> 00:48:57.909
Because it feels like there's
not enough space for us,

00:48:57.909 --> 00:49:00.060
because all of us isn't there.

00:49:00.060 --> 00:49:01.000
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:04.510
DANIELLE KRETTEK: But
this idea of seeking--

00:49:04.510 --> 00:49:07.300
I think, he also said that
everything important he lived--

00:49:07.300 --> 00:49:09.700
or everything important in
his life that he's learned

00:49:09.700 --> 00:49:11.935
has come through his heart
and not through his mind.

00:49:11.935 --> 00:49:12.620
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:49:12.620 --> 00:49:14.536
DANIELLE KRETTEK: And I
think that's something

00:49:14.536 --> 00:49:17.820
that we, as good souls
here at Google, doing

00:49:17.820 --> 00:49:20.842
what we want to do,
good work for the world,

00:49:20.842 --> 00:49:23.050
there is this tension between
the things that we feel

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:25.360
and the things that we know,
the things we can prove

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:27.440
and the things that we intuit.

00:49:27.440 --> 00:49:30.100
And I'm just curious, as
well in this listening

00:49:30.100 --> 00:49:32.320
and in the allowing
of all things,

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:35.140
for this greater
sense of civility,

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:37.441
how does one navigate that?

00:49:37.441 --> 00:49:38.690
KRISTA TIPPETT: Navigate the--

00:49:38.690 --> 00:49:39.480
DANIELLE KRETTEK: This--

00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:40.300
KRISTA TIPPETT: --heart space?

00:49:40.300 --> 00:49:40.510
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Yeah.

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:42.676
And I think you do it so
beautifully with your work,

00:49:42.676 --> 00:49:46.010
because you sit in
conversation with everyone.

00:49:46.010 --> 00:49:47.800
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:49.930
Well, we're going
to have to innovate

00:49:49.930 --> 00:49:52.510
some new forms for that, right?

00:49:52.510 --> 00:49:56.980
Because we don't reward the
time or the energy that--

00:50:01.540 --> 00:50:04.060
yeah, we reward what
comes from the mind

00:50:04.060 --> 00:50:06.880
and not from the heart,
unless you can pitch it

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:08.019
as something that--

00:50:08.019 --> 00:50:09.310
and that's what we do actually.

00:50:09.310 --> 00:50:11.590
Because most of it is--

00:50:11.590 --> 00:50:16.060
all this language we've
always used about "your gut"--

00:50:16.060 --> 00:50:17.770
and now, we've
basically learned that--

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:21.180
what they're calling the
biome, the second brain.

00:50:21.180 --> 00:50:22.750
Like, we've actually known that.

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:23.534
We knew somewhere.

00:50:23.534 --> 00:50:25.450
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Mm--
science is catching up.

00:50:25.450 --> 00:50:26.991
KRISTA TIPPETT: So
I do think science

00:50:26.991 --> 00:50:29.350
is our companion in
being able to make

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:32.170
a rational, serious
argument about this.

00:50:36.290 --> 00:50:40.070
But yeah-- and so I think,
right now, all the structures

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:45.650
we have, they're inadequate.

00:50:45.650 --> 00:50:47.600
And I mean that in
all of our workplaces

00:50:47.600 --> 00:50:51.140
and all of our institutions.

00:50:51.140 --> 00:50:53.870
They're behind on
what we're learning.

00:50:53.870 --> 00:50:57.170
And actually, they're behind on
how actually the world really

00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:04.940
works and how change
really happens

00:51:04.940 --> 00:51:07.850
and on the difference
between what

00:51:07.850 --> 00:51:13.910
is innovative and
transformative, generatively

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:16.380
transformative.

00:51:16.380 --> 00:51:18.660
So that's part of the task.

00:51:18.660 --> 00:51:20.857
And there's no
one-size-fits-all solution.

00:51:20.857 --> 00:51:22.940
And I think that that is
one of these things where

00:51:22.940 --> 00:51:25.400
the repair is going to have
to be everybody starting

00:51:25.400 --> 00:51:27.650
very close to home--

00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:31.720
what you know, what you
touch, the immediate people

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:32.850
and structures around you.

00:51:32.850 --> 00:51:35.290
How do you make space
for that to be rewarded?

00:51:35.290 --> 00:51:38.730
DANIELLE KRETTEK: Mm--
that's interesting--

00:51:38.730 --> 00:51:43.035
the idea of how to reward
the how and the why.

00:51:43.035 --> 00:51:44.574
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:51:44.574 --> 00:51:48.870
DANIELLE KRETTEK: If anybody
has a question for Krista--

00:51:48.870 --> 00:51:50.550
AUDIENCE: My
question is, what is

00:51:50.550 --> 00:51:52.899
your thought behind
always asking someone

00:51:52.899 --> 00:51:54.315
at the beginning
of your podcast--

00:51:54.315 --> 00:51:55.920
KRISTA TIPPETT: Oh, yeah.

00:51:55.920 --> 00:51:59.070
AUDIENCE: --what is something
from their childhood

00:51:59.070 --> 00:52:00.726
that is spiritually
important to them?

00:52:00.726 --> 00:52:01.600
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:52:01.600 --> 00:52:06.180
So I almost always ask some
version of the question of,

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:08.130
was there a religious
or spiritual background

00:52:08.130 --> 00:52:09.400
to your childhood?

00:52:09.400 --> 00:52:11.940
So the truth is that
just about everybody

00:52:11.940 --> 00:52:14.010
has a really
interesting story there,

00:52:14.010 --> 00:52:16.530
whether it's a story of absence
or presence or something

00:52:16.530 --> 00:52:18.550
that was good or bad.

00:52:18.550 --> 00:52:25.200
But the strategic reason I
ask it is because of where

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:26.820
it plants the question.

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:29.730
So again, it's like, the
beginning is everything.

00:52:29.730 --> 00:52:34.570
If you get the beginning
right, you can go places.

00:52:34.570 --> 00:52:37.050
And if you don't, you're
always working really hard

00:52:37.050 --> 00:52:41.310
to get it on the rails.

00:52:41.310 --> 00:52:45.120
So what I've learned
about that place--

00:52:45.120 --> 00:52:48.360
it's true of other questions
about childhood or origins.

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:52.950
So sometimes, if I'm
in a particular setting

00:52:52.950 --> 00:52:56.040
with a theme, I might ask--

00:52:56.040 --> 00:52:59.280
let's say, it's a conversation
about compassion or--

00:52:59.280 --> 00:52:59.850
I don't know.

00:52:59.850 --> 00:53:05.280
And I might say, can you
remember the very first time

00:53:05.280 --> 00:53:07.350
that that word meant
something to you?

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:11.730
Or what is your memory of the
earliest understanding of what

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:14.850
you think of as compassion now?

00:53:14.850 --> 00:53:19.560
The thing about asking somebody
a question that takes them--

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:22.440
what I don't want to
do is start with--

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:26.940
how we present generally-- we
walk in with our credentials

00:53:26.940 --> 00:53:29.170
and what we know
and what we've done.

00:53:29.170 --> 00:53:31.680
And it's very chin up.

00:53:31.680 --> 00:53:33.300
And it's performative.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:37.230
And that's what
we're asked to do.

00:53:37.230 --> 00:53:42.300
That question, it plants people.

00:53:42.300 --> 00:53:45.240
It's not a question that
anybody feels defensive about,

00:53:45.240 --> 00:53:46.730
because I'm not
asking you also--

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:48.396
and I would never ask
somebody-- tell me

00:53:48.396 --> 00:53:49.770
about your spiritual life.

00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:51.780
Are you religious?

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:56.550
That question would be designed
to just make everybody uptight,

00:53:56.550 --> 00:53:57.720
including me.

00:53:57.720 --> 00:54:00.100
If you ask somebody
that question,

00:54:00.100 --> 00:54:05.670
it takes them to a very soft
searching place in their memory

00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:08.950
and, therefore, in their body.

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:12.660
It's also, interestingly-- as
much as we think of religion,

00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:15.660
culturally, as a matter
of convictions and beliefs

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:16.950
and answers--

00:54:16.950 --> 00:54:21.030
it's a place where
beautiful questions reside.

00:54:21.030 --> 00:54:23.940
And it's interesting
to me how many people--

00:54:23.940 --> 00:54:27.760
when they start reflecting
on that part of their life,

00:54:27.760 --> 00:54:30.570
it turns out that there's some
question they asked when they

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:34.832
were 4 or 7 or 9 that
ended up influencing

00:54:34.832 --> 00:54:35.790
the rest of their life.

00:54:35.790 --> 00:54:39.090
Like, some of their life
has been some trajectory

00:54:39.090 --> 00:54:41.880
on the course of that question.

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:45.210
So it's where to start.

00:54:45.210 --> 00:54:49.110
And then everything
follows from there.

00:54:49.110 --> 00:54:51.690
If I can invite people to
be soft and searching right

00:54:51.690 --> 00:54:56.370
up front, then we probably
are going to stay soft

00:54:56.370 --> 00:54:59.091
and searching.

00:54:59.091 --> 00:55:01.590
AUDIENCE: I used to work for
the World Bank as an economist.

00:55:01.590 --> 00:55:03.240
And you talked about
saving the world.

00:55:03.240 --> 00:55:06.720
And then I moved
to Silicon Valley.

00:55:06.720 --> 00:55:09.390
And here, people have
the same intentions.

00:55:09.390 --> 00:55:12.492
And it seems that the
intentionality is right.

00:55:12.492 --> 00:55:14.950
And speaking for the World
Bank, you wouldn't believe that.

00:55:14.950 --> 00:55:16.440
But the same is true.

00:55:16.440 --> 00:55:19.010
People truly believe
in what they are doing

00:55:19.010 --> 00:55:20.890
as doing good in the world.

00:55:20.890 --> 00:55:24.210
So if it's not intentionality,
where do we go wrong?

00:55:24.210 --> 00:55:27.630
Is it that we think it's,
intentionality is right,

00:55:27.630 --> 00:55:29.910
but it's really not,
and it's our ego?

00:55:29.910 --> 00:55:30.715
Or what is it?

00:55:30.715 --> 00:55:31.590
Where do we go wrong?

00:55:31.590 --> 00:55:34.410
And how can we fix
this-- that we start off

00:55:34.410 --> 00:55:36.840
with good intentions and
end up with bad results?

00:55:36.840 --> 00:55:37.751
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

00:55:37.751 --> 00:55:38.250
Right.

00:55:38.250 --> 00:55:39.600
Well, that's a good question.

00:55:39.600 --> 00:55:41.504
Intentionality is
not everything.

00:55:41.504 --> 00:55:43.170
I think, then, I would
want to come back

00:55:43.170 --> 00:55:44.970
to this discernment piece.

00:55:44.970 --> 00:55:48.280
And I do think that--

00:55:48.280 --> 00:55:52.760
yeah, the question of
ego, which is often--

00:55:55.960 --> 00:55:58.260
and of course, our
egos are part of us.

00:55:58.260 --> 00:55:59.510
It's not, you get rid of that.

00:55:59.510 --> 00:56:08.290
But it resides so intimately
with intentionality.

00:56:08.290 --> 00:56:12.450
And so I think, part
of spiritual life--

00:56:12.450 --> 00:56:14.220
of a cultivated interior life--

00:56:17.250 --> 00:56:20.470
is to grow in knowing
the difference.

00:56:20.470 --> 00:56:23.220
Because they often do
feel like the same thing.

00:56:23.220 --> 00:56:27.140
And actually to grow
these other muscles

00:56:27.140 --> 00:56:31.910
around discernment and asking
the how and the why question--

00:56:31.910 --> 00:56:36.680
and the scale of what the
World Bank is working with

00:56:36.680 --> 00:56:39.260
or the scale of what Silicon
Valley is working with

00:56:39.260 --> 00:56:41.220
is tremendous.

00:56:41.220 --> 00:56:44.980
But I do think that
there's something

00:56:44.980 --> 00:56:51.520
we're waking up to a little
late about how disconnected

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:55.600
our view of the problems and,
therefore, the solutions is.

00:56:55.600 --> 00:57:00.250
And this is something about
the post-enlightenment world.

00:57:00.250 --> 00:57:02.500
We were fascinated
with the parts.

00:57:02.500 --> 00:57:05.252
And then we created
this world of parts.

00:57:05.252 --> 00:57:07.210
So in every discipline,
there's this challenge.

00:57:07.210 --> 00:57:09.080
In medicine, there's
this challenge.

00:57:09.080 --> 00:57:11.210
We have specialists for
every part of your body.

00:57:11.210 --> 00:57:13.210
And we didn't learn how
to see the whole and all

00:57:13.210 --> 00:57:14.510
the interactions.

00:57:14.510 --> 00:57:18.070
And there's a corollary to
that in everything we do--

00:57:18.070 --> 00:57:24.120
in the economy, in politics,
in social policies.

00:57:24.120 --> 00:57:29.120
And so, in some
ways-- like, this

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:34.020
is kind of a civilizational
muscle of discernment.

00:57:34.020 --> 00:57:38.510
We actually have to start
to think outside the frames

00:57:38.510 --> 00:57:43.335
that we inherited
and see in a new way.

00:57:46.390 --> 00:57:50.920
But another piece of language
that's really important to me

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:53.740
now is thinking about
having, not just imagination,

00:57:53.740 --> 00:57:55.300
but moral imagination.

00:57:59.380 --> 00:58:03.900
And then, again, discernment--

00:58:03.900 --> 00:58:05.970
there's no prescription.

00:58:05.970 --> 00:58:10.400
It's going to be different
in every setting.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:12.320
But I think there are
muscles we can build up

00:58:12.320 --> 00:58:16.350
and also ways we can help
hold each other accountable.

00:58:16.350 --> 00:58:20.540
AUDIENCE: So in my role here,
