01:07:34.630 --> 01:07:37.780
which I thought was wonderful
because it's an admission

01:07:37.780 --> 01:07:39.310
that we were responsible.

01:07:39.310 --> 01:07:43.620
And you have to admit that to
participate in the healing.

01:07:43.620 --> 01:07:47.770
So I think the stuff that
you're giving us, imparting us,

01:07:47.770 --> 01:07:51.040
is really going to help us.

01:07:51.040 --> 01:07:56.590
I wanted to ask, because
you have, in your own sense,

01:07:56.590 --> 01:07:59.770
the mastery of listening
and interviewing--

01:07:59.770 --> 01:08:03.160
and you say you prepare, and
you do the ritual of being

01:08:03.160 --> 01:08:08.680
hospitable and vulnerability--
all of these things are very,

01:08:08.680 --> 01:08:12.250
to your point,
dynamics that engender

01:08:12.250 --> 01:08:16.720
reciprocal vulnerability
and generosity.

01:08:16.720 --> 01:08:21.830
But when you prepare, you kind
of stop the person, right?

01:08:21.830 --> 01:08:25.689
And so you come,
and then you say

01:08:25.689 --> 01:08:30.279
you're creating an
atmosphere of a safe place.

01:08:30.279 --> 01:08:32.290
And it's interesting,
because I'm

01:08:32.290 --> 01:08:35.200
curious about the correlation
with things like trust

01:08:35.200 --> 01:08:37.779
and what you believe
engenders trust,

01:08:37.779 --> 01:08:41.170
and what you believe
actually builds rapport.

01:08:41.170 --> 01:08:42.720
What are the human
things that you've

01:08:42.720 --> 01:08:43.761
found that build rapport.

01:08:43.761 --> 01:08:45.700
Because Google knows
stuff about you--

01:08:45.700 --> 01:08:47.399
DANIELLE KRETTEK: You're
teasing our next session.

01:08:47.399 --> 01:08:48.024
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:08:48.024 --> 01:08:50.779
So why aren't you
creepy, essentially?

01:08:50.779 --> 01:08:55.092
And what makes your art form
of rapport-building essential?

01:08:55.092 --> 01:08:56.050
I'm curious about that.

01:08:56.050 --> 01:08:56.979
KRISTA TIPPETT: Oh,
that's so interesting.

01:08:56.979 --> 01:08:58.210
Well, yeah.

01:08:58.210 --> 01:09:03.609
I have actually thought
about how the internet has

01:09:03.609 --> 01:09:04.835
changed the work I do.

01:09:04.835 --> 01:09:06.460
Because actually,
when I first started,

01:09:06.460 --> 01:09:09.069
15 years ago, I was
spending a lot of time

01:09:09.069 --> 01:09:11.950
in libraries, just
public libraries.

01:09:14.590 --> 01:09:17.080
And honestly, I don't know
how else I was finding things.

01:09:17.080 --> 01:09:18.247
So it was possible.

01:09:18.247 --> 01:09:19.830
But of course, now,
it's just, there's

01:09:19.830 --> 01:09:23.523
an abundance of information
on anybody, as you say.

01:09:23.523 --> 01:09:25.689
And I can also find things--
which is sometimes fun.

01:09:25.689 --> 01:09:28.105
Like, I can find things people
said 20 years ago that they

01:09:28.105 --> 01:09:30.089
totally forgot that they said.

01:09:30.089 --> 01:09:32.380
And that is a really great
moment in an interview where

01:09:32.380 --> 01:09:34.550
you take them to a
place in themselves

01:09:34.550 --> 01:09:36.791
they haven't been for a while.

01:09:36.791 --> 01:09:37.290
Yeah.

01:09:37.290 --> 01:09:39.069
Why does it not
feel like stalking?

01:09:39.069 --> 01:09:41.430
Because it's appreciative.

01:09:41.430 --> 01:09:48.834
It's appreciative and-- it's
such an interesting question.

01:09:53.100 --> 01:10:03.340
People often say, or sometimes
say after our interviews,

01:10:03.340 --> 01:10:06.760
that it was kind of like I
gave them a gift of themselves.

01:10:06.760 --> 01:10:11.700
Like, I gave them an opportunity
to say things they'd never

01:10:11.700 --> 01:10:14.230
even said to themselves before.

01:10:14.230 --> 01:10:21.480
But I do that by knowing
so well how they think

01:10:21.480 --> 01:10:24.880
and honoring that,
that then we can

01:10:24.880 --> 01:10:29.930
start in a really deep
place and go from there.

01:10:29.930 --> 01:10:34.420
I think, maybe, the
honoring word is important.

01:10:34.420 --> 01:10:36.580
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
And that deep place

01:10:36.580 --> 01:10:40.930
that you hold for them to
return to and share and open up

01:10:40.930 --> 01:10:41.810
themselves--

01:10:41.810 --> 01:10:47.050
I think that human quality
of creating that space,

01:10:47.050 --> 01:10:52.540
that genuine curiosity,
that authentic moment that's

01:10:52.540 --> 01:10:56.080
being created out of
hospitality, like she said--

01:10:56.080 --> 01:10:58.720
it would be curious
to see what changes

01:10:58.720 --> 01:11:02.110
when those values come alive
in the space with technology.

01:11:02.110 --> 01:11:03.105
KRISTA TIPPETT: Yeah.

01:11:03.105 --> 01:11:04.480
DANIELLE KRETTEK:
So we will see.

01:11:04.480 --> 01:11:07.097
That is all of our work
to share here today.

01:11:07.097 --> 01:11:08.180
Thank you so much, Krista.

